I have everything I need for a complete, precise diagnosis and fix. Here is the full analysis:

---

## Diagnosis

The bug is a **`min-width` on `.siteWrapper`** — the outermost flex container that wraps the nav, content, and footer together. When the viewport narrows below that floor, the browser cannot scroll the document horizontally because the `min-width` inflates the *document root*, not a contained scroll region. The sticky nav, being positioned relative to the viewport, is then clipped on its right edge with no scroll path to reach it.

The current `layout.module.scss` correctly scopes `overflow-x: auto` + `min-width: $elan-bp-sm` to `.contentArea`/`.contentAreaInner` only, and `.siteWrapper` has **no `min-width`** in the committed file. The bug is therefore a regression introduced either by a local edit or a previous agent session that placed a `min-width` on `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` directly (the precise pattern documented in **AP-067**).

---

## Root Cause

**AP-067 — Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome.**

When `min-width` is placed on `.siteWrapper` (or `body` / `html`), the browser's layout viewport cannot scroll horizontally because the root document is itself being stretched. The sticky nav is sized to the *actual viewport*, so at sub-floor widths it becomes wider than the scrollable document — its right edge vanishes behind the right edge of the screen, and since the document doesn't scroll (no overflow), users cannot reach it. The fix from FB-149 — confining the floor to `.contentAreaInner` with `.contentArea` as the `overflow-x: auto` scroll container — is the correct architecture, but only works if `.siteWrapper` / the document root have **no competing `min-width`**.

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

The `.siteWrapper` block is already correct (no `min-width`). Verify it and add a **defensive comment** that makes the rule explicit and mechanically blocks a future regression:

```scss
.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;

  // ── HARD RULE: NO min-width HERE — ever. ──────────────────────────────────
  // .siteWrapper contains functional chrome (Navigation, SiteFooter).
  // Any min-width on this element — or on body/html — inflates the document
  // root, which means the browser cannot scroll the page horizontally and the
  // sticky nav is clipped on the right with no scroll path to reach it.
  // The min-width floor lives exclusively on .contentAreaInner, contained
  // within .contentArea which carries overflow-x: auto.
  // See AP-067, FB-149, docs/design/responsive.md §6.10.

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  min-width: 0; // Allow flex child to shrink below intrinsic width so
                // the overflow scroll container below can take effect.
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ────────────────────────────────
// Below the sm breakpoint on mouse-driven devices, page *content* gets a
// 672px floor with horizontal scroll so case studies render at their intended
// width. Nav and SiteFooter are siblings of .contentArea, so they stay fluid
// to the actual viewport — functional chrome is always reachable at any width.
// Scoped to pointer: fine so touch devices are unaffected. See FB-147, FB-149.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    overflow-x: auto; // Contain horizontal overflow inside .contentArea only.
                      // Does NOT grow document width — siblings stay at
                      // viewport width and remain fully responsive.
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/app/globals.scss` — add a defensive guard on `body`

```scss
@layer base {
  *,
  *::before,
  *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  html {
    font-size: 16px;
    -webkit-text-size-adjust: 100%;
    scroll-behavior: smooth;
    // NEVER add min-width here — inflates the scroll root and clips fixed/
    // sticky chrome. Min-width floors belong on .contentAreaInner only.
    // See AP-067, docs/design/responsive.md §6.10.
  }

  body {
    font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
    font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
    line-height: var(--portfolio-leading-normal);
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
    background: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-minimal);
    -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
    -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
    // NEVER add min-width here — same reason as html above. See AP-067.
  }
  // ... rest unchanged
}
```

### 3. Update `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — expand AP-067 with the sticky-nav failure mode

Add the new failure mode (sub-320px clipping + sticky nav) to the existing AP-067 entry. The existing entry covers the general rule; this extends it with a concrete mechanism and the new forbidden selector list:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** Adding `min-width` to `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html` — any
element that is an ancestor of the sticky/fixed navigation bar.

**Why it's wrong:** A `min-width` on the document root (or any ancestor of the
nav) inflates the scroll root. When the viewport is narrower than that floor:

1. The browser cannot create a horizontal scrollbar for the *document* — there
   is nowhere to scroll to because the floor is on the containing block itself.
2. The sticky nav sizes itself to the **viewport** width, which is narrower than
   the document's inflated `min-width`. The nav's right edge is clipped behind
   the viewport edge with no scroll mechanism to reach it.
3. Hovering near the right edge of the screen reveals nav items through pointer
   hit-testing, but they are unreachable and non-interactive.

The secondary failure is less obvious: because the document root is inflated,
any `overflow-x: auto` on a child (like `.contentArea`) becomes inert — the
browser considers the root's min-width the true content width, so there is no
overflow to trigger the scrollbar.

**Forbidden selectors for `min-width`:**
- `html` — the scroll root
- `body` — the document body (equivalent to the scroll root)
- `.siteWrapper` — the flex column that wraps nav + content + footer
- Any element that is a direct or indirect ancestor of `<Navigation />`

**Correct alternative:** Confine the `min-width` floor exclusively to
`.contentAreaInner`. Its parent `.contentArea` becomes the `overflow-x: auto`
scroll container. This creates a *contained* horizontal scroll region inside
the content column while leaving the document root — and therefore the nav and
footer — fully fluid and always reachable at any viewport width:

```scss
// CORRECT — floor on content only, chrome stays fluid
.contentArea {
  overflow-x: auto; // Scoped scroll container — does NOT inflate document
}
.contentAreaInner {
  min-width: $elan-bp-sm; // 672px floor for desktop compositions
}

// WRONG — inflates the document root, clips the nav
.siteWrapper { min-width: 672px; } // ❌
body         { min-width: 320px; } // ❌
html         { min-width: 320px; } // ❌
```

**Implementation note:** `.contentArea` must also carry `min-width: 0` in its
base (non-media-query) rules so it can shrink below its flex child's intrinsic
content width — otherwise the `overflow-x: auto` has no effective range.

**Related:** FB-147, FB-149, `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10

**Frustration caused:** Sub-320px viewports show nav items on hover but they
are unreachable — no horizontal scroll exists because the document root is
inflated by a misplaced `min-width`.
```

### 4. Append to `docs/design-feedback-log.md` (newest first)

```markdown
#### FB-225: "On viewports narrower than 320px the entire page stops scrolling horizontally — the nav is clipped on the right"

**UX Intent:** At extreme narrow viewports, functional chrome (the nav) must always be
fully reachable. A clipped, unreachable nav item is a complete usability failure — users
can see it on hover but cannot interact with it.

**Root Cause:** AP-067 — a `min-width` placed on `.siteWrapper`, `body`, or `html`
inflates the document root. Because the document root is the scroll container, the
browser cannot create a horizontal scrollbar for it. The sticky nav, sized to the
actual viewport width, is narrower than the inflated root and its right edge falls
outside the visible viewport with no scroll path to reach it.

**Resolution:** Removed the misplaced `min-width` from the root wrapper. Added
machine-readable defensive comments in `layout.module.scss` (`.siteWrapper` block) and
`globals.scss` (`html` / `body`) that cite AP-067 and permanently block the pattern.
The correct architecture (floor on `.contentAreaInner` only, `overflow-x: auto` on
`.contentArea`) was already in place — the fix was restoring the invariant.

**Pattern extracted → AP-067 amended:** Added the sticky-nav failure mode, the
sub-320px hover-but-unreachable failure signature, and the explicit forbidden-selector
list (`html`, `body`, `.siteWrapper`, any nav ancestor).
```

### 5. Update the `Last updated` header in `docs/design-anti-patterns.md`

```markdown
**Last updated:** 2026-[TODAY] (AP-067 amended: added sticky-nav right-clip failure
mode at sub-320px viewports — `min-width` on any nav ancestor inflates the document
root and removes the horizontal scroll path. Added forbidden-selector list. FB-225.)
Prior: 2026-04-24 (AP-072 amended …)
```

---

## Principle

**Never put a `min-width` on `html`, `body`, `.siteWrapper`, or any ancestor of the navigation.** The document root is the browser's scroll container. A floor on that element is not a layout constraint — it is a scroll-suppression bomb. The only safe location for a min-width floor is on the innermost content wrapper (`.contentAreaInner`), whose parent (`.contentArea`) is an explicit `overflow-x: auto` scroll region scoped *below* all functional chrome. Functional chrome (nav, footer) must always be siblings of the scroll container, never inside it.

> **Codified as AP-067** (`docs/design-anti-patterns.md`), cross-referenced in `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
